<P>There is a fal&s;e glare of expre&s;&s;ion, and no great ju&s;tne&s;s of &s;entiment, in the&s;e ver&s;es; but they are animated, and flow in a &s;train of poetry. They are pompous and &s;onorous; but the&s;e faults have been reckoned beauties even in poli&s;hed ages. In the &s;ame book our author thus characteri&s;es the different merits of the &s;atires of Horace and Per&s;ius.</P>
