<P>Although we have taken our leave of Robert de Brunne, yet as the &s;ubject is remarkable, and affords a &s;triking por|traiture of antient manners, I am tempted to tran&s;cribe that chronicler's de&s;cription of the pre&s;ents received by king Athel&s;tane from the king of France; e&s;pecially as it contains &s;ome new circum&s;tances, and &s;upplies the defects of our fragment. It is from his ver&s;ion of Peter Langtoft's chro|nicle abovementioned.</P>
