<L><PB N="429" REF="596">
Or make a chartre of land or acquittaunce;</L>
<L>In twentie manir couth he trip and daunce,</L>
<L>After the &s;chole of Oxenfordi tho,</L>
<L>And with his leggis ca&s;tin to and fro.</L>
<L>And pleyin &s;ongis on a &s;male ribible <NOTE N="s" PLACE="foot"><P>v. 224. A &s;pecies of guittar. Lydgate, MSS. Bibl. Bodl. Fairf. 16. In a poem never printed, called <HI>Rea&s;on and Sen&s;ual|lite, compyled by Jhon Lydgate.</HI></P>
<Q><L>Lutys, rubibis, (l. ribibles) and geternes,</L>
<L>More for e&s;tatys than tavernes.</L></Q></NOTE>,</L>
